        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request 4.1 hrs of ALMA and 8.2 hrs of ACA Band 3 observations to complete 76 point mosaic of "El Gordo" with the compact configuration of ALMA's 12-m array (4.4" resolution) to map the central ~5 arcmin of the cluster at 92~GHz, complemented by an 27 point mosaic with the ACA to recover scales ~48'' over the same region and frequency to measure pressure jump search on the shocks as discussed above. 

The required numbers of pointings is set to cover the central region of the cluster and radio relics at Nyquist spacing. The footprint of the mosaics is shown as the black rectangle in the right panel of Figure 2. Integration times on the 12-m array at 92 GHz with a 7.5 GHz bandwidth will provide a sensitivity of 45 muJy per beam. This provides sufficient signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) to detect small-scale features expected as a result of the merger.  The SZ signal from the ACT maps of El Gordo extrapolated to 92 GHz is approximately 30 mJy per beam in the ACT maps (ACT beam is ~1'). This average value scales to 160 muJy per beam for the 4.4' beam for a SNR of ~3.5 for the proposed exposure time per pointing.  This describes the SNR for detection of features with the mean SZ signal of the cluster (i.e., corresponding to yellow and green-colored regions in Fig. 3, right panel). We will detect the more contrasted features in the cluster at SNR ~10-20 (also benefiting from sensitivity contributed by overlapping mosaic fields). In Figure 3 we show the results from the CASA simulation for ALMA, ACA, and their combination (left to right) using the input high-resolution simulated SZ image in the proposed observing configuration. The panels illustrate the effectiveness of our observing strategy at recovering both the fine and wider structure of the SZ signal in "El Gordo."</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
